Dialup Setup

Use Dialup Setup to establish communications between your computer and
other systems, and to maintain the files used to do so. You can
connect to other systems either through direct connection (a cable
connects your system to another) or through a modem (each computer is
connected to a modem and telephone line). With a modem you can access
private computer systems and networks, as well as many commercial
information services, such as CompuServe and Genie.

The following windows are provided for Dialup Setup:

        \k(Dialup Setup Window)

        \k(Dialup Setup: Devices Window)
      
        \k(Dialup Setup: Quick Dial Window)
   
        \k(Dialup Setup: Device Properties Window)

        \k(Dialup Setup: Remote System Properties Window)
^1^Dialup Setup Window
^$20
\k{Dialup Setup}
1. Dialup Setup Window

Use the Dialup Setup window to display all the systems with which you
can currently communicate. This list is read from this file:

	/etc/uucp/Systems file

The \d(buttons^button) available from the Dialup Setup window are:

        \k(Actions Button^^Actions ButtonDS)\t\k(System Button^^System ButtonDS)
        \k(Search Button^^Search ButtonDS)\t\k(Help Button^^Help ButtonDS)
^2^Actions Button=Actions ButtonDS
^$30
1. \k{Dialup Setup Window}
   1.1 Actions Button

The Actions button lets you save changes and exit from the Dialup
Setup window. Clicking on the Actions button displays a menu with the
following options:

        \k(Save Systems List)
        \k(Setup Devices)
        \k(Install)
        \k(Exit)
^3^Save Systems List
^$40
1. \k{Dialup Setup Window}
   1.1 \k{Actions Button^^Actions ButtonDS}
       1.1.1 Save Systems List

The Save Systems List menu option writes any changes you make in the
Dialup Setup window to files on your hard disk (the /etc/uucp/Devices
and /etc/uucp/Systems files are changed). This options makes your
changes permanent.
^3^Setup Devices
^$50
1. \k{Dialup Setup Window}
   1.1 \k{Actions Button^^Actions ButtonDS}
       1.1.2 Setup Devices

The Setup Devices menu option lets you add, delete, and maintain the
ports on your computer that are used for connecting to other systems.
You can also "quick dial" through one of the ports. Clicking on the
Setup Devices menu option displays the Dialup Setup: Devices window.

More information: \k(Dialup Setup: Devices Window)
^3^Install
^$60
1. \k{Dialup Setup Window}
   1.1 \k{Actions Button^^Actions ButtonDS}
       1.1.3 Install

The Install menu option lets you install a remote system icon in any
of your folders. Clicking on the Install menu option opens the Dialup
Setup: Install Remote System Icon window. Enter the folder name where
you want the icon installed in the Location text box. The Dialup
Setup: Install Remote System Icon window has three buttons: Install,
Cancel, and Help.

   o Install Button: This button installs a remote system icon
     in the folder specified in the Location text box.

   o Cancel Button: This button closes the Dialup Setup: Install
     Remote System Icon window with no action taken.

   o Help Button: This button provides on-line help for the Dialup
     Setup: Install Remote System Icon window.

Note: You also can install a remote system icon in another folder with
the \d(drag-and-drop) technique. In the Dialup Setup window, select the
system you want to install. Press and hold the SELECT mouse button and
move the mouse pointer to the folder in which you want the remote
system installed. Release the mouse button.
^3^Exit
^$70
1. \k{Dialup Setup Window}
   1.1 \k{Actions Button^^Actions ButtonDS}
       1.1.4 Exit

The Exit menu option closes the Dialup Setup window. If you make
changes and attempt to exit before you save your changes, a message
window appears with the message:

	Current changes to System List have not been saved.

There are three buttons in the message window: Save Systems List,
Discard, and Cancel.

   o Save Button: This button writes your changes to the file
     (/etc/uucp/Systems) and closes the Dialup Setup window.

   o Discard Button: This button ignores your changes and closes the
     Dialup Setup window (the file /etc/uucp/Systems is not changed).

   o Cancel Button: This button closes the warning window and leaves
     the Dialup Setup window open.
^2^System Button=System ButtonDS
